'''Leninist Group in the Iraqi Communist Movement''' ({{lang-ar|الفريق اللينيني في الحركة الشيوعية العراقية}}) was a grouping of [[Iraq]]i [[communist]] exiles, dissidents from the [[Iraqi Communist Party]]. The main leaders of the group were two university professors at the [[University of Algiers]], Khalid Abdullah as-Salam and Khalil al-Jazairi. Towards the late 1980s, the group began issuing a broadsheet publication, ''Nashrah''.<ref name="ism">Ismael, Tareq Y. ''The Rise and Fall of the Communist Party of Iraq''. [[Cambridge]]/[[New York City|New York]]: Cambridge University Press, 2008. p. 258</ref>
The group signed an appeal of leftist and democratic exiles in the [[Ba'ath Party|Baath]]ist newspaper ''[[Al-Thawra (newspaper)|at-Thawra]]'' in December 1991. In the wake of the [[Gulf War|1991 war]], the Iraqi government issued a pardon for Iraqi exiles. As-Salam and al-Jazairi both returned to Iraq.<ref name="ism"/>
==References== {{Reflist}} [[Category:Defunct communist parties in Iraq]] [[Category:Iraqi Communist Party breakaway groups]] {{Iraq-party-stub}}

{{Infobox referendum | name = Maltese divorce referendum | title = The legalization of divorce in Malta | yes = 122547 | no = 107971 | total = 232691 | electorate = 325102 | map = [[File:Malta Divorce Referendum 2011 Outcome.png|center|300px]] | mapdivision = districts | notes = Note: Saturation of colour denotes strength of vote }} {{Politics of Malta}}
A referendum on divorce was held in [[Malta]] on 28 May 2011. Voters were asked whether they approved of a new law to introduce allowing divorces, as at that time, Malta was one of only three countries in the world (along with the [[Philippines]] and the [[Vatican City]])<ref name="Independent" /> in which divorce was not permitted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5ggvZ-jF8tctPa7jhyr6eQ3oBqWJA?docId=CNG.d73a80696980e3b5a3d31c519ccb3846.4e1|title=Malta to hold divorce referendum in May (AFP) |date=16 March 2011}}</ref> The proposal was approved by 53% of voters, resulting in a law allowing divorce under certain conditions being enacted later in the year.
==Background== A [[private member's bill]] was tabled in the [[Maltese House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] by [[Jeffrey Pullicino Orlando]], a [[Nationalist Party (Malta)|Nationalist]] Member of Parliament.<ref>[http://www.parlament.mt/file.aspx?f=14019 Motion No. 206 – Private Members Bill – Civil Code (Amendt) Bill – (1st Reading) – Presented by Hon Jeffrey Pullicino Orlando MP and Hon Evarist Bartolo MP (the Eleventh Parliament)]</ref> The text of the bill, which had been changed twice, did not provide for the holding of a referendum. This was eventually provided for through a separate Parliamentary resolution under the [[Referenda Act (Malta)|Referenda Act]] authorising a [[non-binding referendum|facultative, non-binding referendum]] to be held.
The Catholic Church in Malta encouraged a "no" vote through a [[pastoral letter]] issued on the Sunday before the referendum day.<ref name="ABC-Australia">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2011/05/31/3231202.htm?section=justin|title=Malta votes to introduce divorce laws|publisher=ABC (Australia)|date=31 May 2011|accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> Complaints were made that religious pressure was being brought to bear upon voters.<ref name="Guardian" /> Around 8 per cent of marriages in Malta are already [[Annulment (Catholic Church)|annulled]] by the Catholic Church.<ref name="Guardian">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/may/27/malta-votes-on-divorce-catholic-church|title=Malta prepares to vote in historic referendum to allow divorce|publisher=The Guardian|date=27 May 2011|accessdate=30 May 2011}}</ref>
==Question== Ballot papers had both English and [[Maltese language|Maltese]] questions printed on them. The English version of the question put to voters was as follows:
{{blockquote|Do you agree with the introduction of the option of divorce in the case of a married couple who has been separated or has been living apart for at least four (4) years, and where there is no reasonable hope for reconciliation between the spouses, whilst adequate maintenance is guaranteed and the children are protected?<ref>[http://www.doi.gov.mt/EN/gazetteonline/2011/03/gazts/GG%2030.3.pdf Writ by the President of Malta dated 28th March, 2011] Department of Information</ref>}}
The question, which resembled the proposal approved by Irish voters in the [[Fifteenth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|Irish divorce referendum of 1995]], was somewhat controversial. It was claimed that it did not reflect the content of the private member's bill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/referendum-question-does-not-reflect-divorce-bill-–-tonio-fenech |title=Referendum question does not reflect divorce bill – Tonio Fenech |publisher=Malta Today |date=16 March 2011 |accessdate=30 May 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525190415/http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/referendum-question-does-not-reflect-divorce-bill-%E2%80%93-tonio-fenech |archivedate=25 May 2011 }}</ref>
==Results== {| class=wikitable style=text-align:right !Choice !Votes !% |- |align=left|For||122,547||53.16 |- |align=left|Against||107,971||46.84 |- |align=left|Invalid/blank votes||2,173||– |- |align=left|'''Total'''||'''232,691'''||'''100''' |- |align=left|Registered voters/turnout||325,102||71.57 |- |align=left colspan=3|Source: [https://web.archive.org/web/20110602010408/http://www.doi.gov.mt/EN/elections/2011/Referendum/final_result.asp Department of Information] |}
Although for the purposes of the referendum the whole country was regarded to be a single constituency - taking into account [[Districts of Malta#Electoral Districts|electoral districts]] - in only three out of the thirteen did the "no" vote reach a majority.<ref name="Independent">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/malta-to-legalise-divorce-after-bitter-referendum-2290802.html|title=Malta to legalise divorce after bitter referendum|publisher=The Independent|date=30 May 2011|accessdate=30 May 2011}}</ref>
==Aftermath== Discussion on the divorce bill started in earnest soon after the result was announced. In the second and third readings a number of MPs still voted against the bill. Parliament approved the law on 25 July. The law came into effect on 1 October.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-14285882 |title=MPs in Catholic Malta pass historic law on divorce |publisher=BBC News |date=25 July 2011 |accessdate=16 July 2011}}</ref>
