[[File:SouthYorkshireParliamentaryConstituency2017Results.svg|thumb|right|[[South Yorkshire]] following the [[United Kingdom general election, 2017|2017 general election]]. For the first time, every seat in the county was held by Labour (red) after this election.{{efn|name=OMara}}]]
The '''People's Republic of South Yorkshire''' or the '''Socialist Republic of South Yorkshire''' were nicknames often given to [[South Yorkshire]] under the left-wing local governments of the 1980s, especially the [[municipal socialism|municipal socialist]] administration of [[Sheffield City Council]] led by [[David Blunkett]], used by both detractors and supporters of the councils.<ref name="Municipal Socialism">{{cite book|quote=[...] local politics in Sheffield were dominated by a particular form of radical municipal socialism, gaining the city a brief but prestigious reputation as the Socialist Republic of South Yorkshire.|title=Redundant Masculinities? Employment Change and White Working Class Youth|author=Linda McDowell|year=2011|isbn=1444355597}}</ref> The councils pursued a social policy radically different from that of [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s national government, following more closely along the lines of [[Militant tendency]]-dominated [[Liverpool City Council]] and the [[Greater London Council]] led by [[Ken Livingstone]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Payling|first=Daisy|date=2014-12-01|title=‘Socialist Republic of South Yorkshire’: Grassroots Activism and Left-Wing Solidarity in 1980s Sheffield|url=https://academic.oup.com/tcbh/article-abstract/25/4/602/1638229/Socialist-Republic-of-South-Yorkshire-Grassroots|journal=Twentieth Century British History|volume=25|issue=4|pages=602–627|doi=10.1093/tcbh/hwu001|issn=0955-2359}}</ref>
The expression was coined by Max Williams, a leader writer at the Yorkshire Evening Post, although it was soon adopted by supporters of the council's left-wing policies.<ref name="Star">{{cite news|quote=The steel city - much of its steel industry wrecked under Thatcher - was at the heart of what used to be proudly called the Socialist Republic of South Yorkshire.|date=2012-08-31|title=Generations Unite|author=Peter Lazenby|newspaper=Morning Star|url=http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/news/content/view/full/123313}}</ref> [[Sheffield Hallam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Hallam]] was the only seat in South Yorkshire where the Conservative Party was a significant political force, the remaining seats being Labour safe seats or [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]]–Labour marginals.<ref name="Atlas">{{cite book|year=1985|title=The Atlas of British Politics|page=135|quote=The Conservatives can win only one seat in the so-called "Socialist Republic of South Yorkshire".|author=Robert Waller|isbn=0709936095}}</ref> Sheffield City Council and the South Yorkshire Metropolitan Authority were solidly left wing, remaining [[socialist]] even as [[Thatcherism]] became the dominant political ideology in the country as a whole.
Sheffield City Council constructed large [[council estates]] with large numbers of communal blocks of flats based on the [[streets in the sky]] philosophy, including the [[Park Hill, Sheffield|Park Hill]] complex,<ref name="MIS">{{cite book|page=65|title=Made in Sheffield: An Ethnography of Industrial Work and Politics|author=Massimiliano Mollona|year=2009|isbn=1845455517}}</ref> and the borough councils of South Yorkshire set up an extensive network of subsidised transport under the [[South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive]].<ref name="Transport">{{cite book|quote=In contrast Labour did have effective control of public transport in the metropolitan counties following the 1981 elections, and their aim, indeed the achievement of the 'Socialist Republic of South Yorkshire', was to run a cheap, efficient and extensive public transport service.|year=1991|title=The State or the market: politics and welfare in contemporary Britain|page=281|author1=Martin Loney |author2=Robert Bocock |lastauthoramp=yes |isbn=0803986424}}</ref> The councils also took more confrontational steps against the Conservative Westminster government. [[Rate-capping rebellion#Sheffield|Sheffield refused to set a budget]] in the [[rate-capping rebellion]], while South Yorkshire declared itself a [[nuclear-free zone]] and a [[demilitarized zone]].<ref name="NFZ">{{cite journal|year=1983|journal=Local Government Review|volume=147|page=99|quote=Councillor Irvine Patnick, the leader of the minority Tory group on the South Yorkshire Metropolitan County Council, apparently makes regular reports to the national chairman of his party and other Conservative high-ups on the situation in that beleaguered county which he refers to either as the Socialist Republic of South Yorkshire or (since the authority declared South Yorks to be a demilitarised and nuclear-free zone) Peace County.|author=Justice of the Peace Ltd}}</ref> The [[red flag (politics)|red flag]] flew on [[Sheffield Town Hall]] on [[May Day]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/pip/mseyw/ |title=Radio 4 - Factual&nbsp;— Children of the Red Flag |publisher=BBC |date=2006-10-16 |accessdate=2009-10-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106175739/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/pip/mseyw/ |archivedate=2012-11-06 |df= }}</ref> and the city signed a [[peace treaty]] with the city of [[Donetsk]] in the [[Ukrainian SSR]], at that point on the other side of the [[Iron Curtain]].<ref name="NFZ"/> Both groups of policies - the practical and the symbolic - were sometimes cited as reasons for the nickname. The [[National Union of Mineworkers (Great Britain)|National Union of Mineworkers]] moved to [[National Union of Mineworkers headquarters|headquarters in Sheffield]] in 1983 in the run-up to the decisive [[UK miners' strike (1984–85)|1984–85 miners' strike]], and the area subsequently became one of the main centres of the strike.<ref name="Milne">{{cite book|year=2004|quote=Sheffield, at the centre of the country's largest coalfield and renowned at the time as the capital of the 'socialist republic of South Yorkshire', offered by far the best deal and it was there that the NUM set up shop in the spring of 1983.|title=[[The Enemy Within (1994 book)]]|page=170|author=Seumas Milne|isbn=1844675084}}</ref>
Although it lost some of its relevance following the Labour Party's shift towards [[New Labour]] and the expulsion of the [[far-left]] elements of the party, along with the replacement of [[Thatcherism]] with the more moderate [[Majorism]] and [[Blairism]], the name remains in use for the area, which is still dominated by the political left. Up until and including the [[United Kingdom general election, 2015|2015 general election]], the only seat in South Yorkshire not held by Labour was Sheffield Hallam; which was held at the time of the election by the-then Leader of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] and [[Deputy Prime Minister]], [[Nick Clegg]]. However, despite not winning, the seat did experience an increase in the Labour vote and the Labour Party candidate Oliver Coppard significantly reduced then-Lib Dem leader Nick Clegg's majority from 15,284 votes to just 2,353 votes.<ref name="Hallam">{{cite book|year=2002|quote=The 'Socialist Republic of South Yorkshire' has not always been as solidly Labour as it is now, with just one Liberal Democrat seat in the shape of Sheffield Hallam breaking the monopoly.|page=302|isbn=0415268338|title=Almanac of British Politics|author=Bryon Criddle|volume=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/main-topics/politics/south-yorkshire-results-labour-hold-barnsley-and-rotherham-heartlands-1-7250383|author=James Reed|title=South Yorkshire results: Labour hold Barnsley and Rotherham heartlands|date=8 May 2015|newspaper=Yorkshire Post|accessdate=2015-06-11}}</ref>. Labour, supported by the left-wing group [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]], gained Sheffield Hallam at the [[United Kingdom general election, 2017|2017 snap general election]] for the first time in their history, while also retaining all of their existing South Yorkshire seats, meaning that Labour controlled every seat in South Yorkshire for the first time. The Labour candidate [[Jared O'Mara]] won a majority of 2,125 votes over Liberal Democrat Nick Clegg, and Clegg's loss was one of the major high-profile losses on the night of 8 June 2017. O'Mara was suspended from the Labour Party on 25 October 2017 after it emerged that he had made derogatory comments online about women and homosexuals, years prior to his election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/18/jared-omara-labour-mp-sheffield-hallam-defeated-nick-clegg|title=Jared O'Mara, the pub-owning first-time MP who won Nick Clegg’s seat |date=18 June 2017|accessdate=27 October 2017|newspaper=The Observer|first=Rachel|last=Cooke}}</ref>{{efn|name=OMara|[[Jared O'Mara]], who won Sheffield Hallam as the Labour candidate in 2017, has since been suspended from the party.}}
As of 2017, all four [[metropolitan borough]] councils – [[Barnsley Metropolitan Borough Council|Barnsley]], [[Doncaster Metropolitan Borough Council|Doncaster]], [[Rotherham Metropolitan Borough Council|Rotherham]] and [[Sheffield City Council|Sheffield]] – are under Labour control, and the Conservatives do not hold a single seat in Rotherham or Sheffield.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/main-topics/politics/yorkshire-s-council-election-results-in-full-success-for-labour-and-tories-1-7251476|author1=Lindsay Pantry |author2=John Roberts |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Yorkshire’s council election results in full: Success for Labour and Tories|date=8 May 2015|newspaper=Yorkshire Post|accessdate=2015-06-11}}</ref>{{efn|Rotherham Metropolitan Borough Council is currently suspended following the [[Rotherham child sexual exploitation scandal]] and the executive is in the hands of Government-appointed commissioners. However, [[Rotherham Metropolitan Borough Council election, 2016|elections were still held in 2016]], at which Labour remained the largest party.}}
