'''''The Stone-Country''''' is a 1967 novel by [[South African]] novelist [[Alex La Guma]].<ref name="Balutansky1990">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aRYR1tnmKpEC&pg=PA60|title=The Novels of Alex La Guma: The Representation of a Political Conflict|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|year=1990|isbn=978-0-89410-558-6|pages=57–80|chapter=The Stone Country: Images of Imprisonment or Imprisonment of Images?|author=Kathleen M. Balutansky}}</ref> The novel is set in a prison, and explores how one prisoner inspires others to pursue [[apartheid|anti-apartheid]] politics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/la-guma-gave-a-voice-to-the-voiceless-1760893|title=La Guma gave a voice to the voiceless|website=IOL|access-date=2016-05-12}}</ref><ref name="CornwellKlopper2012"/> It was the last novel La Guma was able to write before his exile from South Africa.<ref name="CornwellKlopper2012">{{cite book|author1=Gareth Cornwell|author2=Dirk Klopper|author3=Craig Mackenzie|title=The Columbia Guide to South African Literature in English Since 1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j2j_ieNDsU4C&pg=PA121|date=19 June 2012|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-50381-5|pages=120–122|chapter=Alex La Guma}}</ref> The novel was later republished as part of the influential [[African Writers Series]] in 1974.

